>>70050120
Grammar and word choice are what raise my eyebrows.
>Sun takes the moon, taking the sun that takes the moon back.
Switching from "Sun" (personified) to "the sun" (definite noun) but "the moon" in both phrases.

>Time passes while I hone me and my craft.
Myself. "Hone" is a transitive verb where one is both subject and object. "Me" is used when you tell someone else to verb with you as the object. Example: "Give that sunscreen to me, I will put it on myself."

>all my colleagues
All of my colleagues.
>were more of an enemy to me
"Colleagues" is plural, which does not agree with "an enemy." "All of my colleagues were enemies to me."

>competition that rose the grading standards
Object of a transitive verb, so "raised."

>all my hours awarded me
The hours didn't. What you made with them led to, not awards per se. Perhaps, "the hours I invested in them paid dividends" (to use a bit of a cliche) or simply, "my writing was well received."

>and I even kissed whoever
Whomever. Who is for subject, whom is for object.

>I got into board games and sometimes go to a place
Went.

>a place to play with other people any other week.
Any week other than which week? Or did you intend "every other week," which is a phrase indicating once every two weeks?

>I must let sleep take me on its arms until the next morning.
In its arms. In English, arms are treated like a container when they carry something. On would be appropriate for something clinging to one's arms.

>but I see them … during the day, but
Except for transcription of speech where a speaker has been distracted or is of unclear thought, it is very rare that a sentence uses ", but" twice in a row. Other grammatical structures, or two sentences, are preferred.

>I stood over the great ocean, right in a concrete pillar.
If someone's IN a concrete pillar, it's either a construction accident or organized criminals needed to dispose of a body.

Etc. on down the page.
I'm curious: What's your native language?
